Dr. Elizabeth Sherwood-Randall, the Assistant to the President for Homeland Security, led a US delegation to a high-level international conference in Tashkent, Uzbekistan. The conference aimed to promote security, prosperity, and regional connectivity between Central and South Asia and strengthen cooperation with the United States. Dr. Sherwood-Randall highlighted the importance of infrastructure development that aligns with environmental standards and the new G7-led Build Back Better World initiative. She participated in a roundtable meeting of the C5+1 diplomatic platform for Central Asia, where member countries discussed challenges posed by the Covid-19 pandemic and instability in Afghanistan. The delegation also held bilateral meetings with officials from Uzbekistan, Tajikistan, Turkmenistan, and Kazakhstan to enhance security, address humanitarian concerns, and increase vaccinations against Covid-19. They also met with Afghan President Ashraf Ghani, Afghan Foreign Minister Haneef Atmar, and Indian Minister of External Affairs Subrahmanyam Jaishankar to discuss the security situation in Afghanistan and counterterrorism cooperation.